  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.11943" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Sheik Shutter <lb/>or Sheik el Nasara<lb/> April 16 “ 1903</dateline>
        <opener>Dear Sir.</opener>
        <p> Your letter duly received. I must apologize for replying in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.891">English</ref>, but I am afraid a reply in <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.226">
French</ref> might not be sufficiently clear. In reference to a net, mentioned by you, called a „kanôun“ (gamôun), the only time I saw this net in use, was in the Fayoûm<note
            n="1" place="foot"
              type="editorial">„Das Fayyum-Becken, auch Fayum, Fajum, Fajjum oder Faijum, ist ein oasenartiges Becken im Gouvernement al-Fayyum in Ägypten, an das im Nordwesten der Qarun-See anschließt“ (<hi
              rend="unknown" rendition="#none">wikipedia</hi>).</note>, but although of great interest, it did not strike mea s being a very satisfactory mode of catching fish.</p>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>

        <p>You mention that certain methods of catching fish are employed during the inundation, this I have no doubt refers to the long purse-like nets used at the regulators, when the inundation water is being emptied from the basins into the drainage canals, or into other basins.You also refer to a description of a net „pour les muges“. I am not certain whether I have spelt the word right, but suppose you refer to the net or I should rather say nets used in the capture of the Mullet (Mugil)<note
            n="2" place="foot"
            type="editorial">Meeräsche.</note>, whether it is the same net, as that employed in the Mediterranean <pb
            facs="#IMG.3"
            n="3"/> I am unable to say, as my work was confined to the Nile only. I should say that while I was at <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6006">Alexandria</placeName> in a day or two I saw a net being used on the sea shore, an ordinary drag net, the same that is used on the lake (Lake Mengalah) called „gā’ffé“ &amp;amp; practically speaking indentical with that used on the Nile where it is called a „gonraffar“. The chief nets for catching the Mullet are the „she’băkε“ &amp;amp; „towansy“. </p>
        <p>In reference to the „trémail“<note n="3" place="foot"
            type="editorial">„Spiegel-“ oder „Trammelnetz“</note>, the only form of net of which I am aware of, as having been used in ancient times, &amp;amp; which has any resemblance to a net used in the present day, is a <pb
            facs="#IMG.4"
            n="4"/> drag net, a very good example of which may be seen carved on the inner walls oft he temple at Esnet, in which the King is depicted dragging in fish &amp;amp; fowl at the same time. I am afraid what I have written you will be of very little value, but as the nets &amp;amp; modes of fishing employed on the Nile are so numerous &amp;amp; divers, it is very difficult to condense the material into the space of a letter, the names of the various nets also differ a great deal in various parts of <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.5945">Egypt</placeName>. I have written a paper, in which all the various modes of fishing &amp;amp; the different kinds of nets are described, with drawings (??), it will not be published until next year, when the work on the Nile Fish will also appear, but if you would care to have a copy of the paper, I should be very pleased to forward you one, if you will let me know your adress in Europe.<note
            n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">Schuchardt hielt sich zu diesem Zeitpunkt wohl noch in Ägypten auf.</note>
        </p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours very truly</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2059">W. L. S. Loat</persName>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
    </body>
